If the webpage is inserted with some  '\ 0' intentionally, it will throw "java.io.IOException: Input is binaryand unsupported"  in the construction method of **org.jsoup.parser.CharacterReader** and  cannot be parsed

```java
    public CharacterReader(Reader input, int sz) {
        Validate.notNull(input);
        Validate.isTrue(input.markSupported());
        reader = input;
        charBuf = new char[sz > maxBufferLen ? maxBufferLen : sz];
        bufferUp();

        if (isBinary()) {
            throw new UncheckedIOException("Input is binary and unsupported");
        }
    }
  
    private static final int numNullsConsideredBinary = 10; // conservative

    boolean isBinary() {
        int nullsSeen = 0;

        for (int i = bufPos; i < bufLength; i++) {
            if (charBuf[i] == '\0')
                nullsSeen++;
        }

        return nullsSeen >= numNullsConsideredBinary;
    }
```

I consider use "return (double)nullsSeen / bufLength > ratioConsideredBinary " maybe better.
the value of ratioConsideredBinary may be open to question.

```java

    private static final double ratioConsideredBinary = 0.1; // I'm not sure

    boolean isBinary() {
        int nullsSeen = 0;

        for (int i = bufPos; i < bufLength; i++) {
            if (charBuf[i] == '\0')
                nullsSeen++;
        }

        return (double)nullsSeen / bufLength > ratioConsideredBinary;
    }
```
